
                                            The struggle icon died on Friday morning at his Lenasia home after suffering a heart attack.
                                         JOHANNESBURG - President Jacob Zuma has sent his condolences to the family of the late struggle icon Laloo Chiba. The 87-year-old died at his Lenasia home on Friday morning after suffering a heart attack a few days ago.  Chiba was a former Umkhonto we Sizwe platoon commander and was sentenced to 18 years on Robben Island, where he was jailed alongside Nelson Mandela, Walter Sisulu and Ahmed Kathrada.  Presidency spokesperson Bongani Ngqulunga said: “President Zuma has expressed his heartfelt condolences to the Chiba family, relatives and the African National Congress on the loss of this outstanding leader and patriot.” Meanwhile, the memorial and funeral dates have been announced.     